Group Milestone Requirements:\
\
a.) Basic Physics Interaction - Complete\
\
The animation controller for the player was updated while maintaining root motion with a rigid body for basic physics interactions. This rigid body component on player allowed for:\
(1) interactions with colliders \
(2) interactions with triggers\
(3) collider animation during appropriate animations\
(4) added force combined with animation (case for jumping)\
\
b.) Collider animation - Complete \
\
Collider animation was achieved by directly modifying the Collider component of the player for \
(1) crouch - \'91input key c\'92\
(2) vault - \'91input key v\'92\
(3) slide - \'91input key b\'92\
(4) jump - \'91input \'93Jump\'94 in input settings - space\'92\
\
Using this approach some minor bugs in vault and slide collider animation affect game feel. This can be improved using curves with appropriate float parameters to provide smooth collider animation instead of abrupt changes. These abrupt changes lead to the appearance the player can slide through the edge of obstacles.\
\
c.) Ragdoll Simulation - Complete\
\
The rag doll wizard in Unity was used to implement a collider array to allow for rag doll simulation outside of the mecanim animation controller updated in (a). This wizard depended on the model rigging performed via mixamo. The default rag doll wizard was manually updated to improve collider sizing for certain body parts. This is due to the abnormality in the chose avatars body shape.\
\
Limitations in the rag doll simulation include:\
(1) no transition from rag doll back to mecanim animation control. Therefore rag doll simulation is reserved for character death and prompts a level respawn. This is likely the behavior used in the proposed team design project.\
(2) Some non-physical simulation occurs during rag doll simulation. This is likely due to the user of default joint settings after rag doll collider array creation. This can lead to non-realism in joint movement (i.e. the max range of a joint is non-physical)\
\
d.) Game Feel - Complete\
Team 4 Grads+1 proposed an isometric view, chase game for the final design project. Therefore, quick and real time response is key along with multiple camera angles for the isometric viewer.\
\
(1) Real time response control was achieved by combining animation controller work in milestone 1 and lessons learned from the Unity Standard Asset controller. The controller part of the script was adapted from the unity standard asset third person controller. It does not use the blend tree/animations from the standard assets but some of the locomotion functionality is adapted. Like the jump functionality for instance.\
\
(2) The physical and emotional target for our game player is quick, somewhat twitchy physical behaviors with an overall sense of urgency to escape a level, avoid obstacles, and outrun enemies. This ties to the 4 Grads+1 back story in that the main player is an over-worked PhD student who may or may not be under the influence from mind altering substances. This drives the twitchy and urgency characteristics in the character.\
(3) The design team used this milestone to overhaul the entire animation controller to support the aforementioned game feel. The goal was to provide the responsiveness needed for a chase type of game but to stay within the limits of a true physical movement.  This is especially true for turning in the proposed isometric type view game. Multiple camera angles are provided for the player where WASD moves the player game object with respect to the current view. Complete overhaul was required for this game feel since all design team members implemented a traditional 3rd person viewer animation controller in previous work. The standard assets animation controller was used as reference to impose inertia type blend trees for turning within the iso-viewer.\
\
